<div id="review_4214294991" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4214294991" />
    <a title="Emma" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/62643775-emma"><img alt="Emma" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4214294991?book_show_action=true">Sep 02, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Emma" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Emma" href="/user/show/62643775-emma">Emma</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4214294991" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13703477219147634845"><br/>Nataša as a writer does not disappoint with her style. She does cover a wide variety of topics in her writing and this did arouse curiosity in my mind. <br/>If you wonder if this book is safe for the readers that believe in God to read, would it offend, mistreat or abuse various religious views. I think that Nataša always puts an argument in favour of metaphysics, whatever you&apos;d like to call that omniscient, omnipotent, the number one who is consciousness, universe, nature. Nataša&apos;s feminist approach</span>
  <span id="freeText13703477219147634845" style="display:none"><br />Nataša as a writer does not disappoint with her style. She does cover a wide variety of topics in her writing and this did arouse curiosity in my mind. <br />If you wonder if this book is safe for the readers that believe in God to read, would it offend, mistreat or abuse various religious views. I think that Nataša always puts an argument in favour of metaphysics, whatever you'd like to call that omniscient, omnipotent, the number one who is consciousness, universe, nature. Nataša's feminist approach to ancient history is what is missing in the fight between the believers and the 'new-Atheists', philosophers’ arguments that sets in our minds and ignite new thoughts, rifling through unconscious or subconscious clutter scattered in our brain’s cortex.<br /><br />This book is a part of a series of nine books that all discuss 'natural-religion', Nataša begins by placing the Earth at the Age of Enlightenment in her book A-Ma Alchemy of Love, in China of all places, to the East so we can emerge into the mind set of East, and its inhabitants in a cosmic picture, she makes us realize how small we really are she then gives a quick history of humanity through her second novel Tree of Life: A Journey into the Field of Dreams, that leaves us with an adoption story, merging our sub consciousness into myths, poetry, that shows how the Aristotelean heliocentric view of the cosmos was decentred, how Platonic and Pythagorean message of the world as a Music Composition was destroyed by new knowledge with the destruction of the Ancient Egyptian symbolism, alphabet, moved to Ancient Greek mythology and the development of the alphabet.<br /><br />It was a pleasure to be an editor of this book &lt;3 The beauty of it happens to be that it’s set in the Age of Enlightenment, which I really enjoyed as a philosophy student. The author doesn’t shy away from exploring religious taboos and her bluntness is refreshing.</span>
  <a data-text-id="13703477219147634845" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


